Let' face it Spatz; <br>
According to what I've read from your own posting it really was not just the Vietnam War, you opposed. There is a price to pay for living in a free society and you didn't like paying that price.  You lived in the United States during a time of the draft and you were required to register that's the price of being an AMERICAN. Don't blame me because you had to register. I had to register that is the price of freedom.<br>
My belief in AMERICA and in our form of Liberty and justice would not allow me the view you espoused and the views you tried to install upon others.<br>
I was proud to have served,in battle, you didn't like washing bedpans.<br>
I choose to fight for what I believed in. You choose to, well, I really do not know now, what you choose. I guess to serve in changing bedpans. Am I supposed to feel sorry for you because of that?<br>
 Sorry doc that was the form of selective services you choose. As a conscientious objector you could have served in the military but not in a combat zone but from what I see of your posting you were more then a CO. <br>
You opposed and protested, and demonstrated and attempted to prevent others from fulfilling their duties. That is not a Conscientious Objector.  <br>
You are right, however I did look at protestors as longhair freaky people, do you know why? Because they were. Most were drug crazed liberal, and communistic in their thinking, others that joined them were revolutionary and opposed to our form of government and I really could not tell which group was placing flowers in the barrels and which were planting bombs in federal buildings. Those were your associates, mine were the ones that fought for your right to do so.<br><br>
Are we, now supposed to feel sorry for you because you are a JEW? Some of my best friends are JEWS; I learned from the Jews how to go Lion hunting in the snow. To go after the enemies of Israel in their terrorist enclaves, before they strike. You say your not religious, yet I've read where you have struck out at Christians, with the same vicious venom of a Jewish religious fanatic equal to the Jews who persecuted, killed and tortured the Christian's when the Christian church was in infancy. Do I blame my Jewish friends for that today? Get real.<br>
By and large most Conscientious Objectors were supposedly &quot;Christians&quot; but in Nam these so called Christians supplied 74 tons, 86 tons, 32 tons of rice all in bags filled in Sacramento, and shipped from Long Beach and delivered to Communist Forces in Vietnam. It was not just a bag of rice, as you would have others believe. Likewise the medical supplies, supplied by so called Conscientious Objectors were not just Johnson &amp; Johnson Band-Aids.<br><br>
Real conscientious objectors did not protest against the war they did not take active part in trying to SAVE &quot;confused and lost souls&quot; from the dangers of war. Doc you got more men killed in war then you realize. Do you know why?<br>
Because in the heat of battle, when an individual was faced with returning fire or cutting out, the words you utter to them just before they embarked for overseas combat duty may have very well been the turning point in their lives and instead of staying and fighting they froze or ditty mou out of there and today suffer because of that guilt. However, I don't blame them I blame individuals like you that under the banner of a CO installed fear in the hearts of others who were going off to war. <br>
But wasn't it, your God, the God of Abraham, and Jacob who did not want that type of Jew fighting in His wars?<br><br>
&quot;Then the officers shall speak further to the people, and they shall say, 'Who is the man that is afraid and fainthearted? Let him depart and return to his house, so that he might not make his brothers' hearts melt like his heart.&quot; Deut 20:8<br><br>
The Hebrew word used by Moses the JEW  meant, literally, &quot;dissolving or melting,&quot; heart and its applied to the contagious fear which the example of a cowardly soldier produces among his comrades. That's what you produced in soldiers you approached and attempted to stop from serving in the armed forces. I know because during the end of my tour and those that came after me were so minded individuals. But that's not the reason I didn't go back. I did not go back because the war was no longer being fought to win. Because individuals, like you had weaken this nation from within. <br><br>
Because, by then we had begun to lose our pride, this great nation had begun to lose its luster because of individuals like you. The whole nation began to suffer survivor's guilt (sorry Ed,) It all began when this great nation turned its back and abandon millions of Vietnamese to communist subversion and dominion. This happened while we still had a weapon in our hands and a magazine full of ammo. <br>
We called for a cease firing and we stopped firing, but the Communist never stopped firing and we abandoned the Vietnamese to a sorrowful destiny. You speak about saving lives, didn't they count? How many bedpans would you have washed to save a Vietnamese child?  I would have kept firing, but you; you wanted your GI benefits. <br><br>

